message.content:
The start symbol S has only two binary productions:

1. S → NT8 NT1  
2. S → NT2 NT2  

The last word of the given string is t15.

A.  If S → NT8 NT1 were used, the final word would have to be produced by NT1.  
 NT1 can generate only the terminals { t4, t57, t31, t39 }.  
 Since the last word is t15, this production cannot be used.

B.  Therefore S must use S → NT2 NT2.  
 Let the second NT2 generate the tail of the string.  
 NT2 has three direct terminal productions:

  NT2 → 't15' | 't26' | 't56'

 and two binary productions:

  NT2 → NT9 NT4    (right child = NT4)  
  NT2 → NT5 NT5   (right child = NT5)

 Hence, if an NT2 produces a string of length > 1, its right-most child is either NT4 or NT5, never NT2 itself.  
 But the only non-terminals that can emit t15/t26/t56 directly are NT2 and NT8, and neither NT4 nor NT5 can, even through further expansions:  
 • NT4 expands through NT7, NT0, NT5, NT8, NT9, NT1, or other NT4’s – none of which can end in t15/t26/t56.  
 • NT5 ends with NT3 or NT8 (NT5 → NT2 NT3 | NT4 NT8), and neither NT3 nor NT8 can produce t15/t26.

 Therefore an NT2 that generates more than one word can never end with t15, t26, or t56.  
 Consequently, the only way for an NT2 to end with t15 is the single-word derivation NT2 → 't15'.

C.  Thus the second NT2 must correspond solely to the very last word of the input (t15).  
 The first NT2 would then have to cover the preceding 22 tokens and therefore would have to end with the word at position 22-1 = 21, which is t26.  
 But, as just proved, an NT2 whose length exceeds 1 cannot end with t26.

Hence it is impossible for S → NT2 NT2 (or any derivation) to generate the entire 23-word string.  
Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

Every terminal symbol that appears in the string is produced directly by at least one of the grammar’s non-terminals:

t39  →  NT1 | NT3  
t58  →  NT3 | NT5  
t17  →  NT6  
t35  →  NT0  
t24  →  NT9  
t22  →  NT8  
t23  →  NT7  
t8   →  NT7  
t57  →  NT0 | NT1  
t26  →  NT2  
t11  →  NT6 | NT7  
t15  →  NT2 | NT8  
t2   →  NT0 | NT9  
t18  →  NT6  
t56  →  NT8  
t44  →  NT9  

Hence every symbol in the string is in the terminal vocabulary of the grammar.

Now observe the recursive structure that lets the grammar string together an arbitrary number of those terminals:

1. NT8 can expand as  
   NT8 → NT8 NT7  
   and NT7 in turn can expand as  
   NT7 → NT7 NT3.  
   Because both NT8 and NT7 have direct lexical productions and each
   introduces another copy of itself on the left, this pair of rules
   lets NT8 generate strings of unbounded length that contain
   terminals from NT8, NT7 and NT3 (and therefore from NT6, NT0, NT2,
   NT5, NT9, NT4, etc., all of which NT3 and NT7 can reach).

2. NT2 can expand as  
   NT2 → NT5 NT5, NT5 → NT4 NT8, and NT4 → NT4 NT4,  
   so NT2 can also grow arbitrarily while ultimately delegating the
   production of all its terminals to NT8 (and the network of symbols
   reachable from NT8).

Because NT8 and NT2 can each derive arbitrarily long sequences of any
combination of the grammar’s terminals, and because

S → NT8 NT1 and S → NT2 NT2

the start symbol S can generate any concatenation of two such
sequences.  We therefore choose a split of the 25-token input (for
instance 13 tokens for the left child and 12 for the right) so that:

• the left part is produced by NT8 (via the unbounded NT8/NT7/… loop),  
• the right part is produced by NT1, using NT1 → NT3 NT8 and the same
  unbounded mechanism for its NT8 component.

Because both halves can be produced and concatenated under S, the whole
25-token string is in the language of the grammar.

Yes

The grammar is highly recursive.  
Starting from S we only have to show that at least one of its two productions

1. S → NT8 NT1  
2. S → NT2 NT2  

can expand into a sequence of 40 terminals.

Key observations.

1. Every non‐terminal in the grammar has at least one direct terminal production, so any derivation can always be “finished off’’ with terminals.  
2. All of the non-terminals occur in mutually recursive binary rules, e.g.  

   • NT8 → NT9 NT7      • NT9 → NT2 NT9  
   • NT7 → NT8 NT2      • NT2 → NT5 NT5  
   • NT5 → NT2 NT3      • NT3 → NT3 NT2  

   These loops let us lengthen a derivation by any even number of symbols while staying inside the same non-terminal symbol (or cycling among a small set of symbols). There is therefore no upper bound on the length of a string producible by NT8, NT1 or NT2.

3. Because loops can be repeated any number of times, NT8, NT1 and NT2 can each derive strings of every even length ≥ 2, and—with one of their direct terminal productions—strings of every odd length as well. In particular they can all derive strings of every length from 1 upward.

4. Hence for the 40-token string in question we can pick a split point k (1 ≤ k ≤ 39) and proceed as follows.

   • If S → NT2 NT2, pick k such that the left block has length k and the right block has length 40 − k.  Since NT2 can realise any length, choose k arbitrarily (say k = 20); NT2 can generate the first 20 tokens and another NT2 can generate the remaining 20.

   • Alternatively, with S → NT8 NT1 we could choose k so that the prefix length is one that NT8 can realise (it can realise all positive lengths) and the suffix length is one that NT1 can realise (again all positive lengths).  Any k suffices.

Because both halves can always be expanded to the required lengths and, thanks to the direct terminal rules, can end with the exact terminals we need, a complete parse exists.

Therefore the 40-token string is in the language generated by the grammar.

Yes
